long_desc.thetext:
Description of problem: Running `git blame` on some of the files tracked by git triggers it.
Version-Release number of selected component: git-core-2.9.3-2.fc25
Additional info: reporter: libreport-2.8.0 backtrace_rating: 4 cmdline: git blame training.py crash_function: __strcmp_sse2_unaligned executable: /usr/bin/git global_pid: 14285 kernel: 4.9.14-200.fc25.x86_64 pkg_fingerprint: 4089 D8F2 FDB1 9C98 pkg_vendor: Fedora Project runlevel: N 5 type: CCpp uid: 1000
Truncated backtrace: Thread no. 1 (7 frames) #0 __strcmp_sse2_unaligned at ../sysdeps/x86_64/multiarch/strcmp-sse2-unaligned.S:31 #1 verify_working_tree_path at builtin/blame.c:2247 #2 fake_working_tree_commit at builtin/blame.c:2329 #3 cmd_blame at builtin/blame.c:2741 #4 run_builtin at git.c:352 #5 handle_builtin at git.c:539 #6 run_argv at git.c:593

Perhaps this is fixed by https://github.com/git/git/commit/bc6b13a7d (which first appeared in 2.10.0, but applies cleanly to 2.9.3)?
The subject of the commit is "blame: fix segfault on untracked files" while the bug report summary here says it's happening on tracked files. Is that correct?

I've got a scratch build with that upstream patch applied:
https://koji.fedoraproject.org/koji/taskinfo?taskID=18782480
Can you install git-core from there and check whether it resolves the issue you're seeing David? If not, can you provide more details on how to reproduce the issue?
I can confirm it fixes a segfault when calling git blame on an untracked file. Your description says it happens on tracked files, so I want to be sure we're on the same page.
I double checked, and I see I was wrong and the files are indeed not tracked.

I can confirm the patch works. On untracked files, it returns:
fatal: no such path (filepath) in HEAD
